desc: Based on its location in Mościce – an industrial quarter of Tarnów (a medium‐sized city of ~110 000 in the Małopolskie voivodeship which ranks around the Polish average in per-capita output) – this district’s regional GDP falls into the Medium class.

Based on the patterns in the reference data (where small rural Polish settlements regularly fall into the “Low” category and only more industrialized or peri-urban districts reach “Medium” or above) Kwaczała (a village in Alwernia Chrzanowski powiat Małopolskie) is best classified as Low.

Based on the fact that Dziembowo lies in Piła County (a mid‐sized moderately industrialized/rural area of Greater Poland Voivodeship) and comparing it to similar county-level examples (e.g. Warmian-Masurian or Lower-Silesian medium-GDP districts) the most appropriate class is:

Answer: Medium
Based on its location in a moderately prosperous province (Wielkopolskie) but in a rural county (Koniński) Daninów’s district-level GDP most closely aligns with the “Medium” class.

Based on its status as a mid‐sized county seat (around 70 000 inhabitants) a diversified local economy (industry services) but well below the capital’s scale Ostrów Wielkopolski’s district GDP would be classified as: Medium.

Based on its location in Grodziski County (a moderately developed peri-urban area in the relatively strong Wielkopolskie voivodeship) and comparing to the qualitative benchmarks (where only Warsaw reaches “Very High” most rural Polish counties are “Low” and those with some industry or proximity to large metros trend “Medium”) Kotusz in Grodziski is best classed as: Medium.

Based on its location in the Goleniów county (close to Szczecin with significant industrial and transport infrastructure) and benchmarking against similarly placed districts I’d classify its regional GDP as Medium.

Based on its location in a small predominantly rural gmina on the northern outskirts of Wrocław (Trzebnicki powiat Dolnośląskie) which supports only modest local industry and agriculture despite some commuter links the most appropriate class is:

Answer: Medium

Based on its location in the predominantly rural low‐industrial Tuchola County (Kujawsko-Pomorskie) and by analogy with similarly sized non‐industrial Polish districts Wysoka Cekcyn Tucholski would be classified as:  
Answer: Low

Based on its location in rural Podlaskie (Wysokomazowiecki district)—a region with relatively low economic activity and by analogy to similar Podlaskie settlements (e.g. Studzianki) that were classed as “Low”—the appropriate GDP class for Łopienie-Zyski is:

Answer: Low
Based on its location in the largely rural Ciechanowski district of Mazowieckie (outside the Warsaw metro‐area) Glinojeck’s gmina would fall into the “Low” class.

Based on the patterns above (small‐scale rural gminas in Mazowieckie tending toward “Low” but those in the hinterlands of industrialized or higher-output cities – like Olsztyński vs. Olsztyn – edging into “Medium”) Trzepowo Nowe sits in Płocki powiat which while excluding the city proper benefits from spill-over activity around the Płock oil‐refining centre and is more economically robust than the far-eastern Siedlecki area.  I therefore classify Trzepowo Nowe’s district GDP as Medium.  Answer: Medium
Based on Bobot being in the Trenčín Region (Trenčiansky kraj) whose annual GDP (~5–6 billion €) places it in the lower‐mid tier of Slovakia’s eight regions it corresponds to the “Low” class.

Based on its overall economic output (Liberecký kraj’s GDP is on the order of €6–7 billion placing it below the Czech average region but above the lowest tier) it best fits into the “Medium” class.  
Answer: Medium

Based on Bács-Kiskun’s mid-ranking GDP per capita (roughly the Hungarian county average boosted by Kecskemét’s industry) and comparing to the given qualitative bands Soltvadkert (Bács-Kiskun) falls into the Medium class.
